content.description: Start on juggy holds in an orange dike that quickly turns into sloping, flaring cracks, with lots of good side pulls for lay back moves. The crux (just below the roof) is very difficult to protect (on a lead attempt I whipped from the crux, ripped out two cams and almost decked). If you get through the crux, good jugs and knee bar rest await at the roof, followed by an easy top out.
content.protection: small to medium cams and nuts.

content.description: Bolted route just to the left of Orange Peel Wall. Not the best rock quality (a bit dirty also, seems rarely climbed). Work your way through a sequence of small roofs with nice and sometimes cryptic movements. Unfortunately I broke off a jug near the 4th bolt while working on the route, but it shouldn't change the grade of the climb.

Editor's NOTE- When Tumbledown was broken into sub-areas  I had to guess as to the location of this climb. It's a total guess, but the description seems to closely match Dog Leg Corner 5.7 ** on Dorsal Fin, so I put it there. R Hall Admin. Maine  

 "Begin beneath 20ft outside corner. The crux is getting onto it's edge. The edge leads a climber up to a long (5-5) slab."
content.protection: Small to medium stoppers. Tricky placements, no pro up slab. Trees for belay.
content.location: Furthest western crag/slab. Walk west down the road an head up a short distance. Obvious steep short head wall. Rappel off trees or head up and then down easterly.

content.description: This sub-area has a few climbs, nicest of which may be Dog Leg Corner, 5.7 ** and Orange Peel Wall  5.12a **.
